<h1><b>Introduction to data science in R</b>:</br> <i>Data management and the art of wrangling</i></h1>
<hr>
<p><i class="fa fa-bar-chart"></i>
 <b>Overview</b>: In this weekly workshop we will explore the management of data using Program R. We will focus on the stucture and linguistics of data in R. This workshop <b>is not</b> intended to teach specific R tasks. Rather than addressing how to solve data problems, our goal is to explore how to think about data in new ways. Through this process, participants are expected to develop a flexible skillset for managing and exploring data.<img src="https://pbs.twimg.com/media/C-70D_tXUAA8wqz.png"
 title="tidyverse icon"
 alt = "Logo of the tidyverse" 
 align="right"
 width = "200px"
 style= "margin-top: 10px;
  margin-bottom: 10px;
  margin-right:0px;
  margin-left: 20px;"/> Each lesson will last one hour and consist  of a lecture followed by guided activities. This workshop will provide useful knowledge gains for participants at all skill levels. No previous experience with R is necessary.</p>

<p><b>Instructor</b>: Brian S. Evans, Ph.D.</br>
Migratory Bird Center</br>
Smithsonian Conservation Biology Institute</br>
evansbr@si.edu</p>
 
<hr>

<h2>Topics and schedule</h2>

<ol>
<li><b>Base R I</b>: An introduction to the linguistics of Base R and the R Studio environment</li>
<li><b>Base R II</b>: Querying objects in Base R</li>
<li><b>Writing functions</b>: Writing custom functions for repeated tasks</li>
<li><b>The dreaded <i>for loop</i></b>: Writing <i>for loops</i> and confronting myths on their implementation</li>
<li><b>Introduction to the tidyverse: A primer on tidy data</b>: Learning the principles of tidy data and using tidyverse functions to reshape and join data</li>
<li><b>Manipulating and summarizing data in the tidyverse</b>: Learning how to use tidyverse functions for data manipulation and summarizing</li>
<li><b>This <i>is</i> a pipe</b>: Using pipes to streamline and communicate your code</li>
<li><b>Data queries in the tidyverse</b>: Using dplyr to subset data</li>
<li><b>Visualizing data</b>: Using ggplot to plot data</li>
<li><b>Putting it all together</b>: Developing a data science workflow</li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2>Course details</h2>
<ul>
  <li><b>Target audience</b>: Anyone who currently works with data or hopes to in the future</li>
  <li><b>Where</b>: The Science Building conference room. A teleconference link will be provided to off-site participants.</li>
  <li><b>When</b>: Every Wednesday at 3 pm from January 17 - March 21, 2018. Each lesson will last roughly one hour.</li>
  <li><b>Preparation</b>: Please bring your own laptop to each class. Please visit this link prior to attending your first lesson.</li>
</ul>
